"# Chapter 10 — Cortex: introspecting what the program remembers

Cortex is Motoi's persistent memory graph. Book of Jesse Chapter 13 introduced writing to it. This chapter is the introspection lens — how to read what has already been recorded, how to filter, how to trace a value's provenance, how to see across time.

If Cortex is where the program remembers, introspection is how the program answers *what do I remember?*.

## 10.1 The record shape, one more time

Every Cortex record has five fields: subject, predicate, object, at (timestamp), source. This is deliberate — it is what makes provenance queryable.

```scheme
(cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'preferred-color)
;; => ((user preferred-color red 1720000000 ui-click))
```

The return is a list of records. Each record is a five-tuple. You can pull any field.

## 10.2 cortex/query — the introspection verb

`cortex/query` is Cortex's read side. Every keyword argument filters the returned records.

```scheme
(cortex/query :subject 'user)
;; every record about user

(cortex/query :predicate 'preferred-color)
;; every color preference record, across all subjects

(cortex/query :source 'ui-click)
;; every record whose source was ui-click

(cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'preferred-color :order-by 'at)
;; user's color history, chronological
```

The query is composable. Add filters to narrow. Add `:order-by` to sort. Add `:limit n` to cap.

## 10.3 Provenance — the :source field

Every record carries where it came from.

- `:source 'user-explicit-preference` — the user said so
- `:source 'inferred-from-3-choices` — the program guessed
- `:source 'default-guess` — the program had no data and made something up

Filter by source to weight evidence:

```scheme
(cortex/query
  :subject 'user
  :predicate 'preferred-color
  :source 'user-explicit-preference)
;; only what the user actually said, no inferences
```

Provenance is what turns Cortex from a database into an introspection layer. You do not just get facts; you get the story of how each fact came to be a fact.

## 10.4 Time — the :at field

Every record has a timestamp. You can query across time.

```scheme
(cortex/query
  :subject 'user
  :predicate 'preferred-color
  :order-by 'at)
;; chronological history

(cortex/query
  :subject 'user
  :predicate 'preferred-color
  :at :gt (- (current-second) 3600))
;; last hour only
```

Time-aware queries let a program say things like *the user's color changed three times today* or *the last preference was five minutes ago*. This is introspection over time via the same query interface.

