## 10.21 A closing observation

Cortex is what turns a Motoi program from a stateless computation into an accretive process. Introspection over Cortex is what turns that accretion into an observable one.

Without Cortex the program forgets on every run. Without introspection over Cortex the accretion is invisible. Together they give you a program that learns and knows what it has learned.

That is not a small thing. Most programs do neither.

## 10.22 A closing exercise

Try this session. Write three color preferences. Query them back. Introspect.

```scheme
(cortex/record :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color :object 'red :at (current-second) :source 'ui-click)
(cortex/record :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color :object 'red :at (current-second) :source 'ui-click)
(cortex/record :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color :object 'blue :at (current-second) :source 'ui-click)

(cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color)
;; three records

(length (cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color :object 'red))
;; 2 — red was picked twice
```

Two writes, one query, one count. That is the whole rhythm of Cortex introspection. Records in, records out, projections over records to answer specific questions.

Turn the page. Chapter 11 opens the registry.

## 10.23 Deep-seed — one worked provenance walk

Suppose your program shows the user a suggested color. You want to explain why.

```scheme
(define (explain-suggestion subject)
  (define preference
    (car (cortex/query
           :subject subject
           :predicate 'preferred-color
           :order-by 'at :limit 1)))
  (define source (cortex/object-source preference))
  (define supporting
    (cortex/query
      :subject subject
      :predicate 'picked-color
      :source 'ui-click))
  (list
    :suggestion (cortex/object preference)
    :because (list :source source :evidence (length supporting) :records supporting)))

(explain-suggestion 'user)
;; => (:suggestion red
;;     :because (:source inferred-from-3-choices :evidence 3 :records (...)))
```

The verb returns a complete explanation — the suggestion, the source, the count of supporting evidence, and the raw records. If the user asks *why do you keep suggesting red?* you have the answer built in.

## 10.24 Deep-seed — Cortex + registry cross-introspection

Cortex holds facts. The registry holds verbs. They can reference each other.

```scheme
;; record that we used a specific verb
(cortex/record :subject 'session :predicate 'used-verb :object 'map :at (current-second) :source 'trace)

;; introspect verb usage
(define verb-usage (cortex/query :subject 'session :predicate 'used-verb))
;; list of records

;; join with registry to get docs for each used verb
(map
  (lambda (r)
    (let ((v (cortex/object r)))
      (list :verb v :doc (doc-of v))))
  verb-usage)
```

Cortex tells you what was used. The registry tells you what it does. Compose them and you have a personalized usage report.

