Chapter 11 opens the registry — the vocabulary of the language, as a queryable map. Turn the page.

## 10.26 Deep-seed — aggregation

Cortex does not have SQL-style aggregation built in. You build it from primitives.

**Count records matching a filter.**

```scheme
(length (cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color :object 'red))
```

**Group records by a field.**

```scheme
(define (group-by field records)
  (define groups (hash))
  (for-each
    (lambda (r)
      (let ((k (assoc field r)))
        (hash-set! groups k (cons r (hash-ref groups k '())))))
    records)
  groups)

(group-by :object (cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color))
;; => hash of color -> list of records
```

**Distinct values.**

```scheme
(define (distinct-objects records)
  (unique (map cortex/object records)))

(distinct-objects (cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'picked-color))
;; => (red blue green)
```

Three tiny helpers built from primitives. Aggregation over Cortex is a filter followed by a fold, always. Once you know the pattern you can build any aggregation you need in a few lines.

## 10.27 Deep-seed — time-range queries

Cortex supports range predicates on `:at`.

```scheme
;; last hour
(cortex/query :at :gt (- (current-second) 3600))

;; last hour of specific subject
(cortex/query :subject 'user :at :gt (- (current-second) 3600))

;; between two timestamps
(cortex/query :at :between (list start-time end-time))
```

Time-range introspection is what lets you answer questions like *what happened during this specific session?* or *how has the user's behavior changed since we shipped the update?*. Both are one query.

## 10.28 Deep-seed — the whole graph

If you want to see the whole Cortex graph for a subject:

```scheme
(cortex/query :subject 'user)
;; every fact ever recorded about the user
```

That is often a lot of records. Bulk introspection at this scale needs pagination:

```scheme
(cortex/query :subject 'user :limit 100 :offset 0)
;; first 100 records

(cortex/query :subject 'user :limit 100 :offset 100)
;; next 100
```

Or just take a summary:

```scheme
(define user-summary
  (list
    :total-records (length (cortex/query :subject 'user))
    :predicates (distinct-objects (map cortex/predicate (cortex/query :subject 'user)))
    :oldest (car (cortex/query :subject 'user :order-by 'at :limit 1))
    :newest (car (cortex/query :subject 'user :order-by 'at-desc :limit 1))))
```

Four fields describing what the program knows about the user, computed from Cortex introspection primitives. Print it and you have a one-screen summary of a subject's whole history.

Turn the page.

## 10.29 A closing note on doctrine

Cortex is not a database. It is a memory graph. The introspection layer treats it as data — records with fields, queries with filters, projections over the returns.

Every pattern here would work over any store shaped like Cortex. If you have a graph database, the queries port. If you have a triple store, the queries port. The Cortex verb layer is a specific implementation; the introspection reflex generalizes.

If you learn to introspect Cortex well, you have learned to introspect any memory graph. That skill transfers.

Turn the page. Chapter 11 opens the registry — the introspectable map of the language itself.

## 10.30 One more example — the last-N pattern

A common Cortex introspection is *what happened most recently?*. The pattern:

```scheme
(define (last-n subject predicate n)
  (cortex/query
    :subject subject
    :predicate predicate
    :order-by 'at-desc
    :limit n))

(last-n 'user 'picked-color 5)
;; => last five color picks, newest first
```

`last-n` is a five-line helper that becomes the workhorse for any recent-activity display. Every game's HUD, every dashboard, every recent-history widget uses this shape.

## 10.31 Deep-seed — Cortex as substrate for adaptation

Cortex introspection is what lets a program adapt. Without introspection, Cortex would just be a write-only log — no way to consult past facts to decide current behavior.

With introspection:

```scheme
(define (default-color)
  (or (cortex/object (car (last-n 'user 'preferred-color 1)))
      'blue))
```

When the program needs a default color, it introspects Cortex first. If the user has ever expressed a preference, use it. Otherwise fall back.

This tiny pattern is what turns a program from stateless-across-sessions to adaptive. And it is entirely built from Cortex introspection — no separate personalization system needed.

Turn the page. Chapter 11 opens the registry.

## 10.32 A last observation on time

Cortex records have an :at field. That means every query can be time-scoped. Every fact can be historical.

This makes Cortex fundamentally different from a key-value store. Key-value stores overwrite. Cortex accretes. The introspection layer lets you see the accretion.

If you have ever wanted a database that remembers not just the current state but every past state, Cortex is that database. And it introspects the same way as everything else in Motoi — one verb call, one filtered projection.

Turn the page.
